\subsection{General relations and qualitative arguments}

The superfluid pairing of identical fermions is characterized by the order parameter $\Delta({\bf r},{\bf r}\,')=V({\bf r}-{\bf r}\,')$ $\times\langle{\hat\psi({{\bf r}}\,')\hat\psi({{\bf r}})}\rangle$,
where $V({\bf r}-{\bf r}\,')$ is the interaction potential,
the symbol $\langle...\rangle$ denotes the statistical average, 
and $\hat\psi({{\bf r}})$ is the field operator of fermions.
For spin-$1/2$ fermions one of the field operators in the expression for $\Delta({\bf r},{\bf r}\,')$ is for spin-$\uparrow$ fermions,
and the other one for spin-$\downarrow$ fermions.
In free space the order parameter depends on the coordinates ${\bf r}$ and ${\bf r}\,'$ only through the difference $({\bf r}-{\bf r}\,')$.
For a weak attractive interaction the order parameter and the superfluid transition temperature can be found in the BCS approach \cite{note1},
and for both spinless and spin-$1/2$ fermions the renormalized gap equation for the order parameter in the momentum space, 
$\Delta_{\bf{k}}{=}\int{d^2{r}\Delta({\bf r}-{\bf r}\,')\exp\left[{i\bf{k}\left({\bf r}-{\bf r}\,'\right)}\right]}$,
reads (see \cite{Shlyapnikov} and references therein):

